Base:Descriptions.Base:Description: the nave of the Cappella di Santa Caterina

Only slightly longer than it is wide, this intimate chapel is awash in a golden aura of light that reflects off the lacquered luster of the oak paneled walls. Lamplight flickers along the eastern and western walls, the light augmented during the daylight hours by that which floods through the ornate circular stained glass window set high in the northern wall over the altar space. A trio of pews stand on either side of the aisle, a burnished gold wool carpet runner blanketing the expanse from the door to the altar rail. The altar itself is bare of furnishing save for a solitary wooden cross that is silhouetted by the golden hues of the window behind it.

the ornately carved altar rail

Ornately carved to depict lush olive and oak branches entwined together, this dark oak altar rail, also known as a baptismal rail, creates a physical boundary between the penitents of the Catholic faith and the clergy serving God's will from the altar beyond.

the ornate circular stained glass window to the north

Crafted from miniscule panes of glass in hues of gold, bronze, copper, and burgundy, this massive circular stained glass window dominates the upper portion of the northern wall, flooding the space with an aura of golden light by day. Simple in design, the motif within the leaded panes of colored glass displays a representation of the Star of Bethlehem, the rays radiating out from a central point and accented by small burgundy glass panes to lend dimension to the star shape.
